@@yThe Five-City Weave@@N

@@eFive cities form a full-chain legitimacy corridor for goods, people, and
legal authority. Remove any one and the others accumulate strain in specific,
predictable ways. The network is not an alliance. It is a co-dependency that
none fully chose and none can easily exit.@@N

@@W  Midgaard @@d- the inland legitimacy engine. Registries, charters,
  sealed-warrant governance, codified arbitration. The city that other cities
  must reckon with regardless of whether they want to.@@N

@@W  Kiess @@d- the legal-memory city built on Evermeet's ruins along Roc Road.
  Anti-secrecy charter doctrine, three-power governance, and the most
  formally principled anti-Conclave record in the network.@@N

@@W  Kowloon @@d- the northern throughput and labor-delta coordination node.
  The city that moves things and counts them. Its Neon Covenant governance
  is the most institutionally stable of the five.@@N

@@W  Saltglass and Rakuen @@d- the southern hazard screening municipality and
  route-resilience broker. Three times petitioned for annexation into
  Midgaard. Three times refused.@@N

@@W  Mafdet @@d- the maritime legalization authority at the Saltglass Reach's
  terminus, where the inland world meets the sea. Its dual-attestation
  protocol converts inland witness-marked cargo into shipborne contract
  cargo.@@N

@@yTogether they form the chain: @@eorigin claim@@y, then @@eoverland custody@@y,
then @@edispute adjudication@@y, then @@ehazard screening@@y, then @@eocean
transfer@@y.@@N

@@dMidgaard and Kowloon share the deepest tension: both participated in the
Conclave's condemned-debtor transfer apparatus. Both cities' Reckoning
factions seek exposure. Both Continuity factions seek burial. The shared
institutional guilt creates perverse solidarity.@@N

@@eKiess and Midgaard cooperate on road-warden intelligence along the Roc Road
but clash over sealed-warrant governance. Kiess's founding charter was written
specifically to repudiate what Midgaard's Continuity faction insists was
acceptable wartime triage.@@N

@@rRakuen's repeated annexation requests transformed all five-city relations.
Founded to reject Midgaard procedural dominance, it became the city most
insistent on joining that system. The contradiction now drives intercity law.@@N
